# Core Rules

Use **@core** when you need the full set of core project rules in one go.

**Convention**: `@rules/` denotes the rules root (e.g. workspace rules folder or `.cursor/rules`). Resolve relative to your project root.

This rule references the following; for full detail open each:

- **Atomic file rule** *(critical, always on)*: `@rules/core/atomic-file-rule.mdc` — ONE file = ONE export = ONE responsibility; zero helpers; if in doubt, split; use ts-morph for mass refactoring
- **Project & quality**: `@rules/core/project.mdc` — one-thing-per-file, check script
- **General**: `@rules/core/general.mdc` — agent defaults, code style, repo hygiene
- **Pattern selection**: `@rules/core/design-pattern-selection.mdc` — choose Builder/Factory/Adapter/Strategy from real pain points
- **Text hygiene**: `@rules/core/text-hygiene.mdc` — ASCII punctuation and no invisible chars in docs/config
- **JavaScript** (optional): `@rules/javascript.mdc` — cross-runtime JS/TS domain rules
- **Boundaries**: `@rules/core/boundaries.mdc` — where to put routes, components, hooks, utils, services, types
- **Naming & layout**: `@rules/core/naming-and-layout.mdc` — folder layout, file naming, exports
- **Anti-patterns**: `@rules/core/anti-patterns.mdc` — what to avoid (wildcard re-export barrels, inline types, fat handlers)
- **Vertical-slice architecture**: `@rules/core/vertical-slice-architecture.mdc` — refactor module into vertical slice, public API, migration plan, guardrails (use for "vertical slice", "public API", "refactor module")
- **Security baseline**: `@rules/core/security-baseline.mdc` — XSS/secrets/least-privilege defaults

## Short summary

- Many small files; one exported symbol per file; no inline types; no helpers inside components/hooks.
- Choose patterns by pain source: creation, structure, or behavior.
- Route handlers thin: validate → call service → return response.
- Run the project check script after meaningful changes.
- For non-JS/TS stacks, use stack rules directly (`@php`, `@rust`, `@bash`).
